h3. Summary

The REST API document ([https://docs.atlassian.com/software/jira/docs/api/REST/7.12.1/#api/2/reindex-reindexIssues]) mentions that the POST /rest/api/2/reindex/issue endpoint can take JQL as a parameter
{quote}Use either explicitly specified issue IDs or a JQL query to select issues to reindex.
{quote}
However, the endpoint does not explicitly take JQL as a parameter and does not work as described in the document.
h3. Analysis

If we look at the code for the rest endpoint, the logic is simply not there for JQL. It uses [*issueFinder|https://docs.atlassian.com/software/jira/docs/api/7.1.4/com/atlassian/jira/rest/v2/issue/IssueFinder.html] .getIssueObject(issueId))*, which only takes issue keys or id's:
{code:java}
public Response reindexIssues(@QueryParam("issueId") final List<String> issueIds,
                                  @QueryParam("indexComments") @DefaultValue("false") final boolean indexComments,
                                  @QueryParam("indexChangeHistory") @DefaultValue("false") final boolean indexChangeHistory,
                                  @QueryParam("indexWorklogs") @DefaultValue("false") final boolean indexWorklogs) {
        final IssueIndexingParams issueIndexingParams = IssueIndexingParams.builder()
                .setComments(indexComments)
                .setChangeHistory(indexChangeHistory)
                .setWorklogs(indexWorklogs)
                .build();

        //Find all the issues
        List<Issue> issues = new ArrayList<Issue>(issueIds.size());
        for (String issueId : issueIds) {
            issues.add(issueFinder.getIssueObject(issueId));
        }{code}
h3. Suggested Implementation

Correct the documentation or add some details on how to make this work with JQL as outlined in the guide. Otherwise, add the logic to make this work with JQL using the traditional Jira syntax of JQL, E.G.   POST rest/api/2/reindex/issue?jql=project=PROJECTKEY

h3. Summary

Documentation [Connecting Jira applications to MySQL 5.6|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver080/connecting-jira-applications-to-mysql-5-6-967896916.html] for Jira 8.0 recommends the creation of the database with the following parameters:

{code}CREATE DATABASE jiradb CHARACTER SET utf8mb4 COLLATE utf8mb4_bin;{code}

However, at the bottom of the same documentation it also says:

{quote}In this version of MySQL, 4-byte characters (e.g. emojis) aren't supported and will be displayed as question marks (?). They're supported in MySQL 5.7.{quote}

This causes confusion to customers and might lead to errors if the customer follows the procedures in the article.

In our [Jira Documentation Directory|https://confluence.atlassian.com/alldoc/jira-documentation-directory-71598773.html] page, we mention that:
{quote}
This page provides links to all documentation for the Jira applications. We supply documentation for the latest version and previous versions of Jira applications, in both online and offline (downloadable) form.
{quote}

However, the downloadable documentation does not include Jira 8.1 / JSD 4.1 yet. 

Could we add the documentation into the page?

h3. Issue Summary
DVCS extracts an issue key from a commit message using a hardcoded advanced Java regular expression:

{code:java}private static final String SEPARATOR = "[\\s\\p{Punct}]";
private static final String KEY_PREFIX_REGEX = "(?:(?<=" + SEPARATOR + ")|^)"; //zero-width positive lookbehind
private static final String KEY_BODY_REGEX = "(\\p{Lu}[\\p{Lu}\\p{Digit}_]+-\\p{Digit}+)";
private static final String KEY_POSTFIX_REGEX = "(?:(?=" + SEPARATOR + ")|$)";  //zero-width positive lookahead
private static final String ISSUE_KEY_REGEX = KEY_PREFIX_REGEX + KEY_BODY_REGEX + KEY_POSTFIX_REGEX;{code}

However, this is not working in case a release management system uses a special template formatting, which is the case with vRealize Suite Lifecycle Manager (part of vmWare suite) that creates commits like that:

{noformat}[Request=2638][Reference Hash=master][Commit message=PRJ-12634]{noformat}

A solution to this problem could be to make a regex pattern for the issue key extraction configurable (this is how it is done [in Bitbucket|https://confluence.atlassian.com/stashkb/integrating-with-custom-jira-issue-key-313460921.html?_ga=2.171235616.1618673674.1555320550-861429217.1533299002]).

h3. Workaround

Currently, there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available
